Iran of Jan. 3 bombing attack, officials say. Israel rearrests a Palestinian detainee who was freed in a hostage swap in November. The U.S. and U.K. impose new sanctions on four Houthi leaders. U.S. moves toward withdrawing more troops from Iraq. Here\u2019s what to know about the court ruling expected on Friday.  The C.I.A. director is set to talk with Israeli officials about a possible new hostage deal. U.S., Sensing Opportunity, Makes New Push for Gaza Cease-Fire William Burns, the C.I.A. director, planned to meet Israeli, Egyptian and Qatari officials in Europe to try to secure a deal to release the Hamas hostages and a pause in the combat. \u00a0 By   Julian E. Barnes ,\u00a0 Hiba Yazbek ,\u00a0 Aaron Boxerman  and  Roni Caryn Rabin Credit Agence France-Presse \u2014 Getty Images Widening Mideast Crisis: Families of Israeli Hostages Protest at Border Crossing to Block Aid to Gaza Families of hostages have taken more aggressive steps, trying to increase pressure on the Israeli government to give priority to the captives\u2019 return. \u00a0 Credit Alexandre Meneghini\/Reuters Israel Tries to Rebut Genocide Charge by Declassifying Cabinet Decisions South Africa has accused Israel of committing genocide in Gaza. Israel\u2019s legal team has challenged the charge by providing the court with secret orders made by Israel\u2019s civilian and military leaders. \u00a0 By   Patrick Kingsley Credit Remko De Waal\/Agence France-Presse \u2014 Getty Images From Opposite Sides of War, a Hunt for Elusive Facts The Israel-Hamas conflict has produced a prodigious amount of disinformation, putting people who fact-check claims \u2014 especially those who live in the region \u2014 back on their heels. \u00a0 By   Tiffany Hsu  and  Sheera Frenkel Credit Amit Elkayam for The New York Times U.N. Shelter in Besieged Khan Younis Is Struck, and at Least 9 Die United Nations officials said a building that was being used as a shelter by about 800 people had been \u201cclearly marked\u201d as one of their facilities. Israel denied responsibility. \u00a0 By   Hiba Yazbek ,\u00a0 Ameera Harouda  and  Michael Levenson Credit Fatima Shbair\/Associated Press Israel and Hamas\u2019s Cease-Fire and Hostage Deal Proposals: What to Know The negotiations continue, but the sides are far apart on issues including the fate of Hamas\u2019s top leadership in the Gaza Strip. \u00a0 By   Aaron Boxerman ,\u00a0 Patrick Kingsley  and  Adam Rasgon Credit Tyrone Siu\/Reuters Israeli Soldiers Clearing Buffer Zone in Gaza Die in Blast On the deadliest day for Israelis since the ground invasion against Hamas began, about 20 soldiers were killed as they prepared to level buildings near the border. \u00a0 By   Patrick Kingsley ,\u00a0 Ronen Bergman  and  Ameera Harouda Credit Maya Alleruzzo\/Associated Press Maps: Tracking the Attacks in Israel and Gaza See where Israel has bulldozed vast areas of Gaza, as its invasion continues to advance south. \u00a0 By   Lauren Leatherby ,\u00a0 Karen Yourish ,\u00a0 Elena Shao ,\u00a0 Eli Murray ,\u00a0 Scott Reinhard ,\u00a0 Josh Holder ,\u00a0 Agnes Chang ,\u00a0 Eleanor Lutz ,\u00a0 Weiyi Cai ,\u00a0 Pablo Robles ,\u00a0 Leanne Abraham ,\u00a0 Zach Levitt ,\u00a0 Tim Wallace ,\u00a0 Yousur Al-Hlou ,\u00a0 Aric Toler ,\u00a0 Ishaan Jhaveri ,\u00a0 Robin Stein ,\u00a0 Ashley Wu ,\u00a0 Riley Mellen ,\u00a0 John Ismay ,\u00a0 Hiba Yazbek ,\u00a0 Christoph Koettl ,\u00a0 Molly Cook Escobar ,\u00a0 Charlie Smart ,\u00a0 Patrick Kingsley ,\u00a0 Ronen Bergman ,\u00a0 Amy Schoenfeld Walker ,\u00a0 Bora Erden  and  Jon Huang Credit The New York Times Stripped, Beaten or Vanished: Israel\u2019s Treatment of Gaza Detainees Raises Alarm A U.N. office said Israel\u2019s detention and treatment of detainees might amount to torture. It estimated thousands had been detained and held in \u201chorrific\u201d conditions. Some were freed wearing only diapers. \u00a0 By   Raja Abdulrahim Credit Yossi Zeliger\/Reuters Latest Search Search Clear this text input Initial Ruling Expected in Genocide Case Against Israel: What to Know The International Court of Justice is set to issue a decision on Friday that could call on Israel to stop its attacks in Gaza, although it has few means of enforcement. By  Matthew Mpoke Bigg \u00a0 news analysis Plans for Gaza\u2019s \u2018Day After\u2019 Seem Ever Distant The very idea that there will be a clear line between war and peace is misleading, given the politics, security needs and anxieties of all sides. By  Steven Erlanger \u00a0 Qatar Expresses Anger Over Netanyahu\u2019s Leaked Criticism In a recording that aired on Israeli television, a voice that appears to be Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu\u2019s called Qatar\u2019s role as a mediator \u201cproblematic\u201d because of its relationship to Hamas. By  The New York Times \u00a0 \u2018The Daily\u2019: Stories on the Conflict Between Israel and Gaza Listeners of \u201cThe Daily\u201d hear Israelis and Gazans express their fears, hopes and experiences in real time. \u00a0 Shipping Costs Soar in Wake of Red Sea Attacks Ships risking Houthi attacks must pay high insurance premiums, while vessels avoiding the region lose time going around Africa. By  Stanley Reed \u00a0 Britain\u2019s Foreign Secretary Pressures Netanyahu on More Aid for Gaza \u201cThe scale of suffering in Gaza is unimaginable,\u201d David Cameron said after his meeting with the Israeli prime minister, urging a \u201csustainable cease-fire.\u201d By  Mark Landler \u00a0 College Is All About Curiosity. And That Requires Free Speech. True learning can only happen on campuses where academic freedom is paramount \u2014 within and outside the classroom. By  Stephen L. Carter \u00a0 Honed at Home in Yemen, Houthi Propaganda Is Going Global As the war in Gaza gives the Houthi militia an international audience, the group has seized the opportunity to take its message far beyond Yemen\u2019s borders. By  Vivian Nereim \u00a0 Barnard College\u2019s Restrictions on Politic